WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:27.000
The Ghosts of Eddington Castle

00:27.000 --> 00:36.000
on the border of England and Scotland. The year is 1605.

00:36.000 --> 00:38.000
Halt! Who goes there?

00:38.000 --> 00:40.000
Let us in. We have a prisoner.

00:40.000 --> 00:41.000
Who is this man?

00:41.000 --> 00:45.000
Robert Mackenzie. He's a traitor. He has to be hanged.

00:45.000 --> 00:48.000
Place him in the dungeon. Take him to the dungeon.

00:48.000 --> 00:50.000
Get up, Mackenzie.

00:50.000 --> 00:54.000
Take your hands off me, you English pig!

00:54.000 --> 00:57.000
Why you?

00:57.000 --> 01:02.000
Put your sword away. He will be hanged as every traitor should be,

01:02.000 --> 01:05.000
and then his body will be thrown from the castle walls.

01:05.000 --> 01:08.000
Take him to the dungeon.

01:08.000 --> 01:11.000
Put him in there.

01:11.000 --> 01:22.000
The following night, the night before Robert Mackenzie was due to be hanged,

01:22.000 --> 01:26.000
a hay wagon arrived at the gates of the castle.

01:26.000 --> 01:29.000
Halt! Who goes there?

01:29.000 --> 01:32.000
Gabriel West. What is your business here?

01:32.000 --> 01:35.000
You know me. I bring hay for your horses.

01:35.000 --> 01:38.000
Wait. Let me look.

01:38.000 --> 01:40.000
Can I go in now?

01:40.000 --> 01:41.000
You may pass.

01:41.000 --> 01:45.000
Thank you. Get up!

01:45.000 --> 01:48.000
Whoa!

01:48.000 --> 01:52.000
Yes, stupid Mack. Stand still.

01:52.000 --> 01:54.000
Wait a minute.

01:54.000 --> 01:57.000
Who's that?

02:00.000 --> 02:02.000
Don't say a word.

02:02.000 --> 02:05.000
Who are you? And how did you get into my wagon?

02:05.000 --> 02:06.000
Don't ask questions.

02:06.000 --> 02:08.000
I will call for help.

02:08.000 --> 02:10.000
If you do anything, I will kill you.

02:10.000 --> 02:13.000
No, stop. What do you want from me?

02:13.000 --> 02:16.000
Tell me where the dungeons are.

02:16.000 --> 02:19.000
You don't know where the dungeons are.

02:19.000 --> 02:23.000
Can you feel the blade of my knife on your throat?

02:23.000 --> 02:24.000
Alright.

02:24.000 --> 02:27.000
I will kill you if you don't do as I say.

02:27.000 --> 02:28.000
Stop.

02:28.000 --> 02:31.000
Where are the dungeons?

02:31.000 --> 02:33.000
On the other side of this courtyard.

02:33.000 --> 02:35.000
Right.

02:35.000 --> 02:39.000
Now listen to me. Unload your hay and wait here.

02:39.000 --> 02:42.000
I will be back in five minutes.

02:42.000 --> 02:45.000
I intend to leave the castle in your wagon.

02:45.000 --> 02:46.000
I should I wait for you.

02:46.000 --> 02:49.000
Because if you don't, I will kill you.

02:49.000 --> 02:52.000
And what is to stop me leaving the castle without you?

02:52.000 --> 02:54.000
Before you come back.

02:54.000 --> 02:57.000
I have friends outside the castle waiting for this wagon.

02:57.000 --> 03:00.000
If I am not on it, they will kill you.

03:00.000 --> 03:03.000
I will do as you ask.

03:03.000 --> 03:05.000
But why do you want to go to the dungeons?

03:05.000 --> 03:07.000
My husband is there.

03:07.000 --> 03:09.000
Your husband?

03:09.000 --> 03:11.000
The traitor Robert Mackenzie is your husband.

03:11.000 --> 03:14.000
Don't dare use the word traitor in front of me again.

03:14.000 --> 03:17.000
Don't tell me again.

03:17.000 --> 03:20.000
Where are the dungeons?

03:20.000 --> 03:23.000
Across the courtyard and then down some steps.

03:23.000 --> 03:24.000
Thank you.

03:24.000 --> 03:25.000
But you'll never get there.

03:25.000 --> 03:26.000
Why not?

03:26.000 --> 03:29.000
There is a guard at the top of the steps and another at the bottom.

03:29.000 --> 03:31.000
There will not be a problem.

03:31.000 --> 03:34.000
Just make sure you are ready to leave when I return.

03:34.000 --> 03:36.000
And if you breathe a word to these guards,

03:36.000 --> 03:40.000
you will die an ugly death when you leave this castle.

03:40.000 --> 03:42.000
I understand.

03:43.000 --> 03:45.000
I am not waiting for you.

03:45.000 --> 03:47.000
You dangerous witch.

03:49.000 --> 03:50.000
Guard.

03:50.000 --> 03:51.000
Who is there?

03:51.000 --> 03:53.000
It is me.

03:53.000 --> 03:54.000
Who?

03:54.000 --> 03:55.000
Who is it?

03:55.000 --> 03:57.000
Come closer.

03:57.000 --> 03:59.000
Who are you and what?

04:07.000 --> 04:09.000
Who goes there?

04:09.000 --> 04:11.000
Adam is it you?

04:12.000 --> 04:14.000
What is going on?

04:21.000 --> 04:23.000
Who is there?

04:23.000 --> 04:24.000
Is it time?

04:24.000 --> 04:27.000
Robert, it is me.

04:27.000 --> 04:28.000
Elizabeth?

04:28.000 --> 04:29.000
Yes.

04:29.000 --> 04:30.000
Oh my God.

04:30.000 --> 04:31.000
Let me hold you.

04:31.000 --> 04:35.000
Robert, quickly we must leave.

04:35.000 --> 04:36.000
Leave.

04:36.000 --> 04:37.000
Yes, come.

04:37.000 --> 04:38.000
My God.

04:38.000 --> 04:40.000
What have you done?

04:40.000 --> 04:41.000
Have you killed the guard?

04:41.000 --> 04:43.000
I have killed two guards.

04:43.000 --> 04:46.000
I will kill as many as it takes to free you.

04:46.000 --> 04:47.000
Now come.

04:47.000 --> 04:49.000
But how can we escape?

04:49.000 --> 04:50.000
What are we to do?

04:50.000 --> 04:53.000
Robert, there is no time to talk.

04:53.000 --> 04:55.000
Put on this cloak and follow me.

05:02.000 --> 05:05.000
You see the wagon on the other side of the courtyard.

05:05.000 --> 05:06.000
Yes.

05:06.000 --> 05:08.000
We are going to escape in that.

05:08.000 --> 05:09.000
Come on.

05:12.000 --> 05:14.000
Get up.

05:17.000 --> 05:19.000
What the?

05:19.000 --> 05:21.000
The stupid fool.

05:21.000 --> 05:23.000
The wagon has gone.

05:23.000 --> 05:24.000
What's happening?

05:24.000 --> 05:25.000
Quick.

05:25.000 --> 05:27.000
There are horses over there.

05:27.000 --> 05:30.000
We can still get out before they lower the gate.

05:31.000 --> 05:32.000
Stop.

05:32.000 --> 05:33.000
Who are you?

05:33.000 --> 05:35.000
We need two horses.

05:35.000 --> 05:36.000
What?

05:36.000 --> 05:37.000
Oh.

05:37.000 --> 05:38.000
Quickly.

05:42.000 --> 05:43.000
That was the gate.

05:43.000 --> 05:44.000
The prisoner is escaping.

05:48.000 --> 05:49.000
God.

05:49.000 --> 05:50.000
Yes, Captain?

05:50.000 --> 05:51.000
Give me your crossbow.

05:51.000 --> 05:52.000
Yes, Captain.

05:52.000 --> 05:53.000
What are you?

05:56.000 --> 05:57.000
Robert.

05:57.000 --> 05:58.000
Elizabeth.

05:58.000 --> 06:00.000
I've been hit.

06:00.000 --> 06:02.000
Robert, don't stop.

06:02.000 --> 06:04.000
I've been hit.

06:04.000 --> 06:05.000
I'm dying.

06:05.000 --> 06:06.000
Wait.

06:09.000 --> 06:10.000
Hold on to me.

06:11.000 --> 06:13.000
We can ride on one horse.

06:14.000 --> 06:17.000
Elizabeth, save yourself.

06:17.000 --> 06:19.000
Leave me to die here.

06:19.000 --> 06:22.000
Why are you so spineless, Robert?

06:22.000 --> 06:24.000
Hold on to me.

06:30.000 --> 06:32.000
Then horses ask for them.

06:42.000 --> 06:44.000
Leave me, Elizabeth.

06:44.000 --> 06:46.000
Hold on to me, Robert.

06:46.000 --> 06:52.000
If we get beyond the village, we'll be in the forest and there will never catch us.

06:52.000 --> 06:54.000
I can't go on.

06:54.000 --> 06:57.000
I'm bleeding to death.

06:57.000 --> 06:58.000
Wait.

06:58.000 --> 07:00.000
There's house over there.

07:00.000 --> 07:03.000
We can get there before the English scum come over the hill.

07:03.000 --> 07:06.000
We will ask the people in the house to shelter us.

07:06.000 --> 07:08.000
And if they don't.

07:08.000 --> 07:11.000
If they are true Scots, they will help us.

07:14.000 --> 07:17.000
Robert, let me help you.

07:20.000 --> 07:23.000
Lean against the wall.

07:24.000 --> 07:26.000
Go, Princess.

07:26.000 --> 07:27.000
Go.

07:27.000 --> 07:29.000
Run into the forest.

07:35.000 --> 07:36.000
Who's there?

07:37.000 --> 07:39.000
Open the door.

07:39.000 --> 07:40.000
Who are you?

07:40.000 --> 07:42.000
Open the door, I tell you.

07:43.000 --> 07:45.000
Who are you?

07:45.000 --> 07:47.000
And who is this man?

07:47.000 --> 07:48.000
What's happened to him?

07:48.000 --> 07:49.000
Let us in.

07:49.000 --> 07:50.000
Why?

07:50.000 --> 07:52.000
The English are coming after us.

07:52.000 --> 07:54.000
Why are they after you? What have you done?

07:54.000 --> 07:56.000
You were prisoners, aren't you?

07:56.000 --> 07:58.000
You must have escaped from Eddington Castle.

07:58.000 --> 08:00.000
I won't let you and they will kill me.

08:06.000 --> 08:07.000
There we are.

08:07.000 --> 08:08.000
Fire!

08:09.000 --> 08:12.000
Dear God in heaven, you are not coming in here.

08:15.000 --> 08:16.000
Oh my God.

08:18.000 --> 08:22.000
You will regret this moment until your dying day.

08:23.000 --> 08:31.000
In the name of Scotland, I put a curse on your family for all time.

08:32.000 --> 08:33.000
Fire!

08:37.000 --> 08:38.000
Good.

08:39.000 --> 08:40.000
They're both dead.

08:40.000 --> 08:42.000
Oh, God, preserve us.

08:42.000 --> 08:43.000
What is your name?

08:43.000 --> 08:45.000
Andrew McPherson.

08:45.000 --> 08:46.000
You're a Scotsman.

08:46.000 --> 08:47.000
Yes, I have.

08:48.000 --> 08:51.000
This dead man is the traitor, Robert Mackenzie.

08:51.000 --> 08:52.000
Mackenzie?

08:53.000 --> 08:55.000
Why are you giving shelter to traitors?

08:55.000 --> 08:58.000
No, no, I'm not giving them shelter. I promise.

08:58.000 --> 09:01.000
People who shelter traitors are also traitors.

09:01.000 --> 09:05.000
But I didn't shelter them. I wouldn't let them in.

09:05.000 --> 09:06.000
Guards?

09:06.000 --> 09:07.000
Take him away.

09:08.000 --> 09:09.000
Whoop!

09:09.000 --> 09:11.000
I have done nothing wrong.

09:11.000 --> 09:13.000
What is the name of this cottage?

09:13.000 --> 09:15.000
It is known as McPherson's farm.

09:15.000 --> 09:17.000
Burn it to the ground.

09:36.000 --> 09:37.000
Scotland.

09:37.000 --> 09:38.000
2005.

09:38.000 --> 09:39.000
Excuse me.

09:39.000 --> 09:40.000
Yes?

09:40.000 --> 09:43.000
Are you Walter McPherson?

09:43.000 --> 09:44.000
Yes, I am.

09:44.000 --> 09:45.000
Oh!

09:45.000 --> 09:46.000
How amazing!

09:46.000 --> 09:47.000
Sorry?

09:47.000 --> 09:50.000
Well, I've just finished reading your book.

09:50.000 --> 09:51.000
Oh.

09:51.000 --> 09:52.000
Oh.

09:52.000 --> 09:53.000
Oh.

09:53.000 --> 09:54.000
Oh.

09:54.000 --> 09:55.000
Oh.

09:55.000 --> 09:56.000
Oh.

09:56.000 --> 09:57.000
Oh.

09:57.000 --> 09:58.000
Oh.

09:58.000 --> 09:59.000
Oh.

09:59.000 --> 10:00.000
Oh.

10:00.000 --> 10:01.000
Oh.

10:01.000 --> 10:02.000
Oh.

10:02.000 --> 10:03.000
Oh.

10:03.000 --> 10:05.000
Hey, I love you, Jean.

10:05.000 --> 10:07.000
Zhang, it's pretty easy.

10:07.000 --> 10:09.000
Why don't we finish drawing your book?

10:09.000 --> 10:10.000
Which one?

10:10.000 --> 10:12.000
I've written quite a few.

10:12.000 --> 10:15.000
The Ghost of Ed agentan castle.

10:15.000 --> 10:16.000
It's brilliant.

10:16.000 --> 10:17.000
Thank you.

10:17.000 --> 10:19.000
My name's Jean Duncan, by the way.

10:19.000 --> 10:22.000
Please am each you miss...

10:22.000 --> 10:23.000
Ms Duncan...

10:23.000 --> 10:25.000
Oh.

10:25.000 --> 10:26.000
Call me Jane.

10:26.000 --> 10:27.000
Please am each you Jane.

10:27.000 --> 10:29.000
Tell me.

10:29.000 --> 10:33.000
Really? I'm actually from Eddington.

10:33.000 --> 10:35.500
Are you? Do you live there?

10:35.500 --> 10:40.000
No, I live in Edinburgh. I'm coming home to see my parents.

10:40.000 --> 10:41.500
I see.

10:42.000 --> 10:45.000
Walter, are you English, aren't you?

10:45.000 --> 10:46.500
Oh, you noticed.

10:46.500 --> 10:50.000
I certainly did. I'm surprised.

10:50.000 --> 10:52.000
Surprised? Why?

10:52.000 --> 10:57.000
I thought that the ghosts of Eddington Castle was written by someone from the area.

10:57.000 --> 11:02.000
Well, for a start, my ancestors are from the area around Eddington.

11:02.000 --> 11:06.500
Right. McPherson is a very common name in the area.

11:06.500 --> 11:09.500
And secondly, I own a house in Eddington.

11:09.500 --> 11:12.500
Do you know? Which one?

11:12.500 --> 11:14.500
McPherson's farmhouse.

11:16.500 --> 11:20.000
You own McPherson's farmhouse?

11:20.000 --> 11:24.500
Yes. Well, I inherited it from my cousin, Alistair.

11:24.500 --> 11:27.500
Oh. Was he?

11:27.500 --> 11:30.500
Was he the man who died there? Yes.

11:30.500 --> 11:36.000
Alistair McPherson? Yes, I see. How long?

11:36.000 --> 11:38.500
It was five years ago.

11:38.500 --> 11:41.000
And is it true?

11:41.000 --> 11:43.000
What? Is what true?

11:43.000 --> 11:48.000
Is it true that he only spent one night at the house before he died?

11:48.000 --> 11:53.000
Yes, it is. He died of a heart attack on his first night in the house.

11:53.000 --> 11:54.500
Very strange.

11:54.500 --> 11:57.000
I see.

11:57.000 --> 11:59.000
You know people in the village think...

11:59.000 --> 12:03.000
I know. I know they think that the farmhouse is haunted.

12:03.000 --> 12:04.000
Yes.

12:04.000 --> 12:08.500
Well, I'm not sure. For a start, it isn't the original farmhouse.

12:08.500 --> 12:12.500
The original farmhouse burnt down. This one is only 200 years old.

12:12.500 --> 12:16.500
I know, but it's built on exactly the same spot.

12:16.500 --> 12:17.000
Really?

12:17.000 --> 12:20.500
Really? And take my work for it, Walter.

12:20.500 --> 12:25.500
People in Eddington believe that the farmhouse and the castle are haunted.

12:25.500 --> 12:28.500
So many strange things have happened there.

12:28.500 --> 12:31.500
I know. I spent months researching that book.

12:31.500 --> 12:35.500
I know all about the horses galloping across the hills near the castle late at night.

12:35.500 --> 12:38.500
Well, a lot of people have heard them.

12:38.500 --> 12:39.500
Have you?

12:39.500 --> 12:41.500
Well, no.

12:41.500 --> 12:46.500
You see? You actually ask anyone if they've seen these horses and they say,

12:46.500 --> 12:49.500
No, but my uncle McPavish has.

12:49.500 --> 12:55.500
So, I asked if I could meet these uncles and grandfathers and of course they were all dead.

12:55.500 --> 12:56.500
Well...

12:56.500 --> 13:01.500
Anyway, I don't care. It's my house and I'm going to live there.

13:01.500 --> 13:05.500
You're going to live at McPherson's farmhouse.

13:05.500 --> 13:06.500
Yes.

13:06.500 --> 13:08.500
What? At the weekends?

13:08.500 --> 13:09.500
No. All the time.

13:09.500 --> 13:11.500
Goodness!

13:11.500 --> 13:14.500
Well, you feel safe there.

13:14.500 --> 13:19.500
Safe? Jane, I've lived in London for the last 20 years.

13:19.500 --> 13:25.500
In my street, every day I see tramps, drug dealers, hooligans, football fans.

13:25.500 --> 13:27.500
I've had enough.

13:27.500 --> 13:29.500
You've had enough of London?

13:29.500 --> 13:31.500
Absolutely. It's dirty and expensive.

13:31.500 --> 13:35.500
And I'm a writer, not a banker, so I can't afford to live there anymore.

13:35.500 --> 13:36.500
I see.

13:36.500 --> 13:40.500
And I'm too old for it. Everyone seems to be under 30.

13:40.500 --> 13:42.500
How old are you?

13:43.500 --> 13:44.500
31.

13:44.500 --> 13:47.500
Goodness. I'm 31.

13:47.500 --> 13:51.500
I was joking, Jane. I'm a little bit older than 31.

13:51.500 --> 13:54.500
Anyway, I decided it was time for a change.

13:54.500 --> 14:00.500
But... you want to live in McPherson's farmhouse?

14:00.500 --> 14:04.500
No one has lived there for ages. I mean apart from...

14:04.500 --> 14:06.500
Apart from Alistair, I know.

14:06.500 --> 14:08.500
But I am going to live there.

14:08.500 --> 14:12.500
In fact, I moved all my books and a lot of my furniture up there last month.

14:12.500 --> 14:15.500
And a nice lady from the village has cleaned the place up for me.

14:15.500 --> 14:17.500
She's done a wonderful job.

14:17.500 --> 14:19.500
I'm sure she has.

14:19.500 --> 14:22.500
Eddington people are very hardworking.

14:24.500 --> 14:26.500
Tell me something, Walter.

14:26.500 --> 14:27.500
What?

14:27.500 --> 14:31.500
Have you ever spent the night at the farmhouse?

14:31.500 --> 14:33.500
Not yet, no.

14:33.500 --> 14:35.500
Tonight will be the first night.

14:38.500 --> 14:43.500
Melrose, next station. Melrose, change here from McGovern, Haven and Eddington.

14:43.500 --> 14:45.500
We have to change here.

14:45.500 --> 14:46.500
Okay.

14:57.500 --> 14:58.500
Walter.

14:59.500 --> 15:00.500
What?

15:00.500 --> 15:01.500
Wake up.

15:01.500 --> 15:02.500
Why?

15:02.500 --> 15:03.500
We've arrived.

15:03.500 --> 15:04.500
Where are we?

15:04.500 --> 15:05.500
In Eddington.

15:05.500 --> 15:06.500
Oh.

15:06.500 --> 15:07.500
Right.

15:10.500 --> 15:12.500
How are you going to get to the farmhouse?

15:12.500 --> 15:14.500
I don't know.

15:14.500 --> 15:15.500
Like taxi, I suppose.

15:15.500 --> 15:16.500
Taxi!

15:16.500 --> 15:19.500
At this time of night, no chance.

15:19.500 --> 15:20.500
Oh.

15:20.500 --> 15:22.500
Well, I'll walk.

15:22.500 --> 15:23.500
Walk?

15:23.500 --> 15:24.500
Don't be silly.

15:24.500 --> 15:27.500
It's about three miles outside the village.

15:27.500 --> 15:30.500
At that case, I don't know what I'll do.

15:30.500 --> 15:34.500
Look, my father will be waiting for me outside the station.

15:34.500 --> 15:36.500
He can give you a lift.

15:51.500 --> 15:54.500
It's awfully nice of you to give me a lift, Mr. Duncan.

15:54.500 --> 15:56.500
Think nothing of it, Mr. McPherson.

15:56.500 --> 16:00.500
Walter thought you would be able to get a taxi at the station father.

16:01.500 --> 16:06.500
Well, there is a taxi in the village, but the driver stops work at six o'clock.

16:06.500 --> 16:09.500
I don't know how I would have done without you.

16:09.500 --> 16:12.500
In London, I go everywhere by bus or taxi.

16:12.500 --> 16:15.500
I don't have a car, waste of time and money.

16:15.500 --> 16:17.500
What did you see?

16:17.500 --> 16:20.500
It's a waste of time and money, owning a car.

16:20.500 --> 16:21.500
Really?

16:21.500 --> 16:23.500
Well, not up here, of course.

16:23.500 --> 16:26.500
I'm sure you need a car all the time up here.

16:26.500 --> 16:27.500
Yes.

16:27.500 --> 16:29.500
I'm sure we do.

16:29.500 --> 16:31.500
We're coming to the farmhouse now.

16:44.500 --> 16:45.500
Goodness.

16:45.500 --> 16:46.500
It's dark out here, isn't it?

16:46.500 --> 16:47.500
Yes, it is.

16:47.500 --> 16:48.500
Very dark.

16:48.500 --> 16:54.500
I say, Mr. Duncan, could you point your headlights at the front door so I can see what I'm doing?

16:54.500 --> 16:56.500
Eh, just a minute.

17:00.500 --> 17:02.500
That's marvellous. Thank you.

17:13.500 --> 17:15.500
Well, here we are.

17:15.500 --> 17:17.500
Home sweet home.

17:17.500 --> 17:19.500
Do you want to come in and have a look around?

17:19.500 --> 17:20.500
Eh.

17:20.500 --> 17:21.500
Come on.

17:21.500 --> 17:22.500
Don't be shy.

17:22.500 --> 17:23.500
Jean!

17:23.500 --> 17:24.500
Don't go in there!

17:24.500 --> 17:25.500
Father!

17:25.500 --> 17:27.500
I mean it!

17:27.500 --> 17:30.500
I don't mind driving, Mr. McPherson, here.

17:30.500 --> 17:33.500
But I don't want you to go into the house.

17:33.500 --> 17:34.500
Sorry, Mr. McPherson.

17:34.500 --> 17:36.500
It's nothing personal.

17:36.500 --> 17:38.500
No, no, I understand.

17:38.500 --> 17:39.500
You country types?

17:39.500 --> 17:41.500
I beg your pardon?

17:41.500 --> 17:42.500
Sorry, I mean...

17:42.500 --> 17:46.500
Walter, Dad and I are going home now.

17:46.500 --> 17:48.500
Here's my phone number.

17:48.500 --> 17:51.500
If you need anything, just give me a call.

17:51.500 --> 17:53.500
Well, thank you.

17:53.500 --> 17:55.500
Do you have a phone here?

17:55.500 --> 17:57.500
Ah, no, not yet.

17:57.500 --> 17:59.500
But I've got a mobile.

17:59.500 --> 18:00.500
Here.

18:00.500 --> 18:01.500
The numbers on this card.

18:01.500 --> 18:02.500
Okay.

18:02.500 --> 18:05.500
I'll call you later to make sure everything is alright.

18:05.500 --> 18:06.500
Goodbye.

18:08.500 --> 18:09.500
Hmm.

18:09.500 --> 18:10.500
Thank you, Jane.

18:10.500 --> 18:12.500
Thanks for everything.

18:12.500 --> 18:13.500
Jean!

18:13.500 --> 18:14.500
Coming!

18:26.500 --> 18:34.500
Good God.

18:34.500 --> 18:36.500
It's quiet around here.

18:36.500 --> 18:38.500
And it's so dark.

18:44.500 --> 18:46.500
What on earth is that?

18:49.500 --> 18:51.500
Pull yourself together, Walter.

18:51.500 --> 18:54.500
It's time to have a look at your new home.

18:55.500 --> 18:58.500
Now where the hell is the light switch?

18:59.500 --> 19:01.500
Don't blast.

19:01.500 --> 19:03.500
The lights aren't working.

19:03.500 --> 19:04.500
Oh, well.

19:04.500 --> 19:06.500
I'll have to sort that out in the morning.

19:06.500 --> 19:08.500
So...

19:08.500 --> 19:11.500
the bedroom's in here, I think.

19:16.500 --> 19:18.500
Jesus Christ, it's a cat.

19:18.500 --> 19:20.500
How the hell did you get in here?

19:20.500 --> 19:22.500
Well, you're going out.

19:23.500 --> 19:25.500
How'd you go?

19:29.500 --> 19:30.500
Oh, my God.

19:30.500 --> 19:32.500
There's that noise again.

19:32.500 --> 19:33.500
There we are.

19:33.500 --> 19:34.500
Fire!

19:34.500 --> 19:36.500
Walter, pull yourself together.

19:36.500 --> 19:38.500
There are no ghosts at Eddington Castle.

19:42.500 --> 19:43.500
Time for bed.

19:44.500 --> 19:46.500
I wish to God there was some whiskey somewhere.

19:50.500 --> 19:51.500
What?

19:52.500 --> 19:53.500
Where am I?

19:54.500 --> 19:55.500
Hello?

19:55.500 --> 19:56.500
Walter?

19:56.500 --> 19:57.500
Who's that?

19:57.500 --> 19:58.500
It's Jane.

19:58.500 --> 19:59.500
Jane Duncan.

19:59.500 --> 20:01.500
It's Jane.

20:01.500 --> 20:02.500
Oh, Jane.

20:02.500 --> 20:03.500
Hello.

20:03.500 --> 20:04.500
What time is it?

20:04.500 --> 20:06.500
It's half past ten.

20:06.500 --> 20:08.500
Sorry, did I wake you up?

20:08.500 --> 20:09.500
No, no.

20:09.500 --> 20:10.500
I was just...

20:11.500 --> 20:13.500
Well, yes, you did actually.

20:13.500 --> 20:15.500
I'm so sorry, Walter.

20:15.500 --> 20:17.500
I should have waited until tomorrow.

20:17.500 --> 20:20.500
I just wanted to see if everything was alright.

20:21.500 --> 20:23.500
Yes, everything's fine.

20:23.500 --> 20:25.500
There's no electricity and no whiskey,

20:25.500 --> 20:27.500
but apart from that, no problems at all.

20:27.500 --> 20:30.500
Well, I'm very pleased to hear it.

20:30.500 --> 20:33.500
I was wondering what your plans were for tomorrow.

20:33.500 --> 20:35.500
Well, I hear it.

20:36.500 --> 20:38.500
My God, what was that?

20:38.500 --> 20:39.500
What?

20:39.500 --> 20:41.500
What is it, Walter?

20:41.500 --> 20:43.500
Someone's knocking on the door.

20:43.500 --> 20:44.500
Fit to wake in the dead.

20:44.500 --> 20:45.500
Can't you hear it?

20:45.500 --> 20:47.500
No, Walter.

20:47.500 --> 20:49.500
I can't hear anything at all.

20:49.500 --> 20:51.500
Open the door.

20:51.500 --> 20:53.500
I still might.

20:53.500 --> 20:54.500
Did you hear that?

20:54.500 --> 20:55.500
No.

20:55.500 --> 20:57.500
What's going on?

20:57.500 --> 21:00.500
There's a woman at the door shouting ahead of.

21:00.500 --> 21:02.500
I'm going to tell her to get lost.

21:02.500 --> 21:04.500
Walter, don't.

21:04.500 --> 21:06.500
Don't open the door.

21:06.500 --> 21:08.500
Hold on a second, Jane.

21:08.500 --> 21:09.500
I'll sort it out.

21:09.500 --> 21:11.500
Walter, stop it.

21:11.500 --> 21:13.500
Don't open the door.

21:13.500 --> 21:15.500
Open the door.

21:15.500 --> 21:17.500
I've just about had enough.

21:19.500 --> 21:21.500
Open the door.

21:21.500 --> 21:22.500
Who's there?

21:22.500 --> 21:24.500
Open the door, I tell you.

21:24.500 --> 21:25.500
But who are you?

21:25.500 --> 21:27.500
Open the door.

21:27.500 --> 21:29.500
They're going to kill us.

21:29.500 --> 21:31.500
Who are you?

21:31.500 --> 21:33.500
My God.

21:33.500 --> 21:34.500
What's happened to this man?

21:34.500 --> 21:36.500
The English are after us.

21:36.500 --> 21:38.500
The English, what are you talking about?

21:38.500 --> 21:39.500
Let us in.

21:39.500 --> 21:40.500
No.

21:40.500 --> 21:42.500
Tell me who you are.

21:42.500 --> 21:44.500
What the hell?

21:44.500 --> 21:46.500
Who are all these people?

21:46.500 --> 21:51.500
Oh, my God.

21:51.500 --> 21:56.500
You will regret this moment until your dying day.

21:56.500 --> 22:04.500
In the name of Scotland, I put a curse on your family for all time.

22:04.500 --> 22:05.500
Fire!

22:05.500 --> 22:11.500
Oh, my God.

22:11.500 --> 22:13.500
It's all true.

22:17.500 --> 22:20.500
Walter, what's happened?

22:20.500 --> 22:24.500
Walter!

22:24.500 --> 22:25.500
Hello.

22:25.500 --> 22:27.500
Is that the police?

22:27.500 --> 22:28.500
Yes, it is.

22:28.500 --> 22:32.500
My name is Jane Duncan, and I'm calling from Eddington.

22:32.500 --> 22:33.500
Eddington.

22:33.500 --> 22:36.500
Now, that's near Haberne, am I right?

22:36.500 --> 22:37.500
Yes.

22:37.500 --> 22:39.500
You have to send someone.

22:39.500 --> 22:41.500
Something terrible has happened.

22:41.500 --> 22:42.500
Really?

22:42.500 --> 22:44.500
Now, what would that be?

22:44.500 --> 22:46.500
I think someone may have been murdered.

22:46.500 --> 22:47.500
Murdered?

22:47.500 --> 22:48.500
Where?

22:48.500 --> 22:50.500
McPherson's farmhouse.

22:50.500 --> 22:57.500
Please get police and an ambulance there as fast as you can.

22:57.500 --> 22:58.500
Father?

22:58.500 --> 22:59.500
What is it, Jane?

22:59.500 --> 23:01.500
We have to go back to the farmhouse right away.

23:01.500 --> 23:02.500
Why?

23:02.500 --> 23:03.500
What's happened?

23:03.500 --> 23:10.500
Walter is in terrible trouble.

23:10.500 --> 23:11.500
Oh, my God.

23:11.500 --> 23:14.500
Walter's at the door.

23:14.500 --> 23:16.500
Walter, are you all right?

23:16.500 --> 23:17.500
Please, no more.

23:17.500 --> 23:18.500
He's alive.

23:18.500 --> 23:20.500
Father, here's my phone.

23:20.500 --> 23:22.500
Call the police again.

23:22.500 --> 23:23.500
Hi.

23:23.500 --> 23:26.500
Walter, can you hear me?

23:26.500 --> 23:27.500
Yes.

23:27.500 --> 23:29.500
What happened?

23:29.500 --> 23:31.500
A man and a woman.

23:31.500 --> 23:32.500
They were trying to get in.

23:32.500 --> 23:33.500
A man and a woman?

23:33.500 --> 23:34.500
Yes.

23:34.500 --> 23:36.500
What did they look like?

23:36.500 --> 23:37.500
I don't know.

23:37.500 --> 23:38.500
Oh, no.

23:38.500 --> 23:39.500
God.

23:39.500 --> 23:41.500
Did it hit me?

23:41.500 --> 23:43.500
Did what hit you, Walter?

23:43.500 --> 23:44.500
The arrow.

23:44.500 --> 23:45.500
The arrow.

23:45.500 --> 23:46.500
Did it hit me?

23:46.500 --> 23:47.500
No, Walter.

23:47.500 --> 23:48.500
It didn't hit you.

23:48.500 --> 23:49.500
Thank God for that.

23:49.500 --> 23:50.500
Jane.

23:50.500 --> 23:51.500
What, Father?

23:51.500 --> 23:53.500
The ambulance is on its way.

23:53.500 --> 23:54.500
Good.

23:54.500 --> 23:55.500
Thank you.

23:55.500 --> 23:56.500
Is he all right?

23:56.500 --> 23:58.500
Well, he's alive, but he isn't all right.

23:58.500 --> 24:02.500
I think he's had a heart attack or something, and...

24:02.500 --> 24:04.500
And?

24:04.500 --> 24:21.500
I think he's seen the ghosts of Elizabeth and Robert Mackenzie.

24:21.500 --> 24:24.500
My name is Detective Sergeant Jackson, and you are...

24:24.500 --> 24:28.500
My name's Jane Duncan, and this is my father, Donald.

24:28.500 --> 24:29.500
Hello.

24:29.500 --> 24:30.500
Hello.

24:30.500 --> 24:31.500
Sorry to keep you both waiting.

24:31.500 --> 24:32.500
That's all right.

24:32.500 --> 24:35.500
We just wanted to make sure that the gentleman was on his way to hospital.

24:35.500 --> 24:36.500
I understand.

24:36.500 --> 24:38.500
Is he going to be all right?

24:38.500 --> 24:39.500
I don't know.

24:39.500 --> 24:41.500
He's had a heart attack.

24:41.500 --> 24:43.500
The medics did what they could.

24:43.500 --> 24:44.500
We'll have to wait and see.

24:44.500 --> 24:45.500
Okay.

24:45.500 --> 24:49.500
Now, if you don't mind, I need to ask you one or two questions.

24:49.500 --> 24:50.500
I know it's a bit late.

24:50.500 --> 24:51.500
That's all right.

24:51.500 --> 24:52.500
It's not a problem.

24:52.500 --> 24:53.500
Right.

24:53.500 --> 24:57.500
Well, first of all, I understand that you found the gentleman.

24:57.500 --> 24:58.500
Yes.

24:58.500 --> 25:00.500
Where was he when you found him?

25:00.500 --> 25:02.500
He was lying in the doorway.

25:02.500 --> 25:05.500
And did he tell you what had happened to him?

25:05.500 --> 25:11.500
Not exactly, but I think he saw the ghosts of Eddington Castle.

25:11.500 --> 25:12.500
He...

25:12.500 --> 25:13.500
He saw what?

25:13.500 --> 25:15.500
He saw two ghosts.

25:15.500 --> 25:16.500
Er...

25:16.500 --> 25:18.500
I can't write that in my report.

25:18.500 --> 25:22.500
Mr. Jackson, you aren't from round here, are you?

25:22.500 --> 25:24.500
No, I'm from Glasgow.

25:24.500 --> 25:27.500
Did you see your ruined castle when you drove here?

25:27.500 --> 25:30.500
No, it's dark. I didn't see anything.

25:30.500 --> 25:34.500
Well, you drove past Eddington Castle.

25:34.500 --> 25:38.500
Most people around here would tell you that there are ghosts there.

25:38.500 --> 25:40.500
Ghosts, see?

25:40.500 --> 25:41.500
Anybody famous?

25:41.500 --> 25:45.500
Detective, this is no laughing matter.

25:45.500 --> 25:48.500
The ghosts are two Scottish freedom fighters.

25:48.500 --> 25:50.500
Elizabeth and Robert Mackenzie.

25:50.500 --> 25:54.500
They fought against the English in the 17th century.

25:54.500 --> 25:57.500
They were killed somewhere in these fields.

25:57.500 --> 26:01.500
People have seen the ghosts of the English soldiers who killed them as well.

26:01.500 --> 26:02.500
I see.

26:02.500 --> 26:05.500
Well, let's talk about what happened this evening.

26:05.500 --> 26:10.500
By the way, what is your relationship with the gentleman?

26:10.500 --> 26:13.500
I met him on the train from Eddington at this evening.

26:13.500 --> 26:15.500
We gave him a lift to the farmhouse.

26:15.500 --> 26:16.500
I see.

26:16.500 --> 26:19.500
So you were here when he had the heart attack?

26:19.500 --> 26:20.500
No.

26:20.500 --> 26:22.500
We brought Mr. McPherson here.

26:22.500 --> 26:25.500
But my father didn't want to go into the house.

26:25.500 --> 26:27.500
Really? Why not?

26:27.500 --> 26:30.500
Everyone in Eddington is frightened of this house.

26:30.500 --> 26:33.500
No one has lived here for five years.

26:33.500 --> 26:37.500
Walter, Mr. McPherson, owns the cottage now.

26:37.500 --> 26:41.500
But tonight was the first night he spent here.

26:41.500 --> 26:43.500
He tried to spend here.

26:43.500 --> 26:44.500
Right.

26:44.500 --> 26:49.500
And the last person who lived here died the first night he was here.

26:49.500 --> 26:51.500
So, let me get this straight.

26:51.500 --> 26:57.500
Mr. McPherson is the owner of the cottage, but he's never spent any time here.

26:57.500 --> 26:58.500
That's right.

26:58.500 --> 27:03.500
So, you brought Mr. McPherson to the house and then you went home?

27:03.500 --> 27:04.500
Yes.

27:04.500 --> 27:06.500
So, why did you come back to the cottage?

27:06.500 --> 27:08.500
I came because...

27:08.500 --> 27:09.500
Yes?

27:09.500 --> 27:13.500
Well, I called Walter to see if he was all right.

27:13.500 --> 27:14.500
Yes?

27:14.500 --> 27:17.500
And something happened while we were on the phone.

27:17.500 --> 27:20.500
He said there was someone at the door.

27:20.500 --> 27:23.500
He opened the door and started talking to someone.

27:23.500 --> 27:25.500
Did you hear who he was talking to?

27:25.500 --> 27:26.500
No.

27:26.500 --> 27:28.500
I could only hear Walter's voice.

27:28.500 --> 27:30.500
What did he see?

27:30.500 --> 27:32.500
He said, he said...

27:32.500 --> 27:34.500
Who are you?

27:34.500 --> 27:35.500
My God.

27:35.500 --> 27:36.500
What's happened to this man?

27:36.500 --> 27:37.500
The English.

27:37.500 --> 27:39.500
What are you talking about?

27:39.500 --> 27:40.500
No.

27:40.500 --> 27:41.500
Tell me who you are.

27:41.500 --> 27:42.500
What the hell?

27:42.500 --> 27:44.500
Who are all these people?

27:44.500 --> 27:46.500
Oh, my God.

27:46.500 --> 27:47.500
It's all true.

27:47.500 --> 27:48.500
It's all true.

27:48.500 --> 27:49.500
It's all true.

27:49.500 --> 27:51.500
It's all true.

27:53.500 --> 27:55.500
Mr. McPherson?

27:55.500 --> 27:56.500
Mr. McPherson?

27:56.500 --> 27:58.500
What?

27:58.500 --> 28:01.500
Oh, nice.

28:01.500 --> 28:02.500
What time is it?

28:02.500 --> 28:04.500
It's half past nine.

28:04.500 --> 28:06.500
Mr. McPherson and you have a visitor.

28:06.500 --> 28:08.500
Good morning, Walter.

28:08.500 --> 28:09.500
Jane.

28:09.500 --> 28:11.500
How good to see you.

28:11.500 --> 28:13.500
Good to see you too, Walter.

28:13.500 --> 28:14.500
Oh, great.

28:14.500 --> 28:15.500
Yes.

28:15.500 --> 28:16.500
And they're letting me out today.

28:16.500 --> 28:17.500
I know.

28:17.500 --> 28:21.500
Walter, I'm sorry I didn't come to see you earlier.

28:21.500 --> 28:23.500
I had to go back to Edinburgh.

28:23.500 --> 28:25.500
But I came back as soon as I could.

28:25.500 --> 28:28.500
It's so good to see you, Jane.

28:28.500 --> 28:31.500
You know you saved my life, don't you?

28:31.500 --> 28:32.500
Oh, Walter.

28:32.500 --> 28:33.500
It was nothing.

28:33.500 --> 28:34.500
No.

28:34.500 --> 28:36.500
You're wrong.

28:36.500 --> 28:38.500
The doctors told me.

28:38.500 --> 28:41.500
If you hadn't come to the house, I would have died.

28:41.500 --> 28:45.500
Well, only too glad to help.

28:45.500 --> 28:47.500
It was terrifying, you know.

28:47.500 --> 28:50.500
I can imagine.

28:50.500 --> 28:54.500
This woman, she looked as if she was going to kill me.

28:54.500 --> 28:55.500
Yes.

28:55.500 --> 28:58.500
And do you know what the man said?

28:58.500 --> 29:08.500
He said, in the name of Scotland, I put a curse on your family for all time.

29:08.500 --> 29:10.500
A curse?

29:11.500 --> 29:17.500
Your family is cursed because the man in the farmhouse didn't let Robert and Elizabeth into the house.

29:17.500 --> 29:20.500
Well, it seems that way.

29:20.500 --> 29:24.500
Walter, this may seem like a ridiculous question, but...

29:24.500 --> 29:26.500
Go on.

29:26.500 --> 29:28.500
Are you going to go back to the farmhouse?

29:28.500 --> 29:29.500
No way.

29:29.500 --> 29:30.500
Are you sure?

29:30.500 --> 29:32.500
Absolutely.

29:32.500 --> 29:38.500
I'm going to put it on the market, and if no one wants to buy it, I'm going to set fire to it.

29:38.500 --> 29:40.500
I don't think you should do that.

29:40.500 --> 29:44.500
I think there's something we can do to solve the problem.

29:44.500 --> 29:45.500
We?

29:45.500 --> 29:46.500
Yes.

29:46.500 --> 29:47.500
We.

29:47.500 --> 29:48.500
I'll help you.

29:48.500 --> 29:54.500
Walter, you and I are going to spend the night at the farmhouse tonight.

29:54.500 --> 29:56.500
What?

29:56.500 --> 29:58.500
No way.

30:05.500 --> 30:07.500
Thank you very much, Mr. Pearson.

30:07.500 --> 30:08.500
You're welcome.

30:08.500 --> 30:09.500
How much is that?

30:09.500 --> 30:11.500
Oh, nothing, Jean.

30:11.500 --> 30:12.500
This trip is on the house.

30:12.500 --> 30:14.500
Oh, thank you.

30:23.500 --> 30:25.500
I can't believe that I'm doing this.

30:25.500 --> 30:27.500
Walter, trust me.

30:27.500 --> 30:29.500
We're doing the right thing.

30:30.500 --> 30:39.500
Well, are you going to come in this time?

30:39.500 --> 30:40.500
Of course.

30:40.500 --> 30:42.500
You won't be able to see anything.

30:42.500 --> 30:43.500
Yes, I will.

30:43.500 --> 30:45.500
I brought these.

30:45.500 --> 30:46.500
Campals.

30:46.500 --> 30:48.500
Good idea.

30:53.500 --> 30:57.500
Oh, Walter, it's absolutely beautiful.

30:58.500 --> 30:59.500
Yes.

30:59.500 --> 31:00.500
You're right.

31:00.500 --> 31:01.500
I'd forgotten.

31:01.500 --> 31:04.500
By the way, what does your father think about you being here?

31:04.500 --> 31:06.500
He doesn't know.

31:06.500 --> 31:07.500
He doesn't know?

31:07.500 --> 31:08.500
No.

31:08.500 --> 31:09.500
He thinks I'm in Edinburgh.

31:09.500 --> 31:12.500
I haven't told him that I came back.

31:12.500 --> 31:14.500
Jean, this is crazy.

31:14.500 --> 31:16.500
Walter, relax.

31:16.500 --> 31:21.500
We just have to spend the night here, and then everything will be fine.

31:21.500 --> 31:23.500
You know there isn't any electricity.

31:23.500 --> 31:24.500
Yes.

31:24.500 --> 31:27.500
So I can't even make you a cup of tea.

31:27.500 --> 31:29.500
But I do have this.

31:29.500 --> 31:30.500
A bottle of whiskey.

31:30.500 --> 31:31.500
Do you want some?

31:31.500 --> 31:32.500
No.

31:32.500 --> 31:34.500
And you mustn't have any either.

31:34.500 --> 31:37.500
You had a heart attack less than a week ago.

31:37.500 --> 31:38.500
I know.

31:38.500 --> 31:41.500
That's why I want some whiskey.

31:41.500 --> 31:44.500
So, what do we do now?

31:44.500 --> 31:46.500
We wait.

31:46.500 --> 31:50.500
Jean, if you want to sleep, you can have my room.

31:50.500 --> 31:52.500
I can sleep here in the kitchen.

31:52.500 --> 31:54.500
Walter, I don't need to...

31:54.500 --> 31:55.500
Shh.

31:58.500 --> 31:59.500
Can you hear that?

31:59.500 --> 32:00.500
Yes.

32:00.500 --> 32:02.500
Oh, God.

32:02.500 --> 32:04.500
Can we call the police or something?

32:04.500 --> 32:06.500
We don't need the police.

32:06.500 --> 32:08.500
Let me go to the window.

32:08.500 --> 32:09.500
No.

32:09.500 --> 32:12.500
Walter, just stay where you are.

32:18.500 --> 32:20.500
Robert, let me help you.

32:21.500 --> 32:23.500
Lean against the wall.

32:23.500 --> 32:25.500
Go, Princess.

32:25.500 --> 32:26.500
Go.

32:26.500 --> 32:28.500
Run into the forest.

32:35.500 --> 32:36.500
Jane.

32:36.500 --> 32:37.500
Wait.

32:37.500 --> 32:39.500
Open the door.

32:41.500 --> 32:43.500
Don't move, Walter.

32:43.500 --> 32:45.500
Let me deal with this.

32:45.500 --> 32:46.500
Jane.

32:46.500 --> 32:47.500
What are you doing?

32:48.500 --> 32:50.500
I'm going to open the door.

32:50.500 --> 32:51.500
Jane, don't.

32:51.500 --> 32:52.500
They'll kill you.

32:52.500 --> 32:53.500
Walter.

32:53.500 --> 32:54.500
Trust me.

32:54.500 --> 32:57.500
Open the door.

32:59.500 --> 33:00.500
Welcome.

33:00.500 --> 33:02.500
Come in.

33:02.500 --> 33:05.500
You are letting us come in?

33:05.500 --> 33:06.500
Yes.

33:06.500 --> 33:08.500
Robert, come.

33:09.500 --> 33:10.500
I can't.

33:10.500 --> 33:11.500
Come.

33:11.500 --> 33:12.500
Come inside the house.

33:12.500 --> 33:13.500
Sorry.

33:14.500 --> 33:16.500
Oh, thank you.

33:16.500 --> 33:18.500
We are escaping from the English.

33:18.500 --> 33:19.500
I know.

33:19.500 --> 33:21.500
You are welcome here.

33:21.500 --> 33:23.500
We are friends.

33:23.500 --> 33:25.500
My husband is dying,

33:25.500 --> 33:28.500
but I don't want the English to catch him.

33:28.500 --> 33:29.500
I...

33:29.500 --> 33:30.500
Listen.

33:34.500 --> 33:36.500
They've gone.

33:36.500 --> 33:39.500
Robert, we are safe.

33:39.500 --> 33:42.500
Robert, we are safe.

33:42.500 --> 33:43.500
Safe.

33:43.500 --> 33:44.500
Safe.

33:44.500 --> 33:45.500
Safe.

33:45.500 --> 33:46.500
Safe.

33:46.500 --> 33:47.500
Safe.

33:47.500 --> 33:48.500
Safe.

33:48.500 --> 33:49.500
Safe.

33:55.500 --> 33:56.500
If disappeared.

33:56.500 --> 33:58.500
Yes.

33:58.500 --> 34:01.500
And I don't think they will come again.

34:01.500 --> 34:03.500
Jane, you...

34:03.500 --> 34:05.500
You are amazing.

34:05.500 --> 34:07.500
Thank you, Walter.

34:07.500 --> 34:09.500
I don't know what to say.

34:09.500 --> 34:11.500
Don't say anything.

34:11.500 --> 34:14.500
Welcome to your new home.

34:14.500 --> 34:18.500
I hope you spend many happy days here.

34:18.500 --> 34:20.500
I hope so too.

34:20.500 --> 34:22.500
Oh, my God.

34:22.500 --> 34:24.500
I really need a whiskey now.

34:24.500 --> 34:30.500
Walter, whiskey is not a good idea for someone who's just had a heart attack.

34:30.500 --> 34:37.500
Jane, meeting the ghosts who gave me the heart attack in the first place wasn't such a good idea.

34:37.500 --> 34:41.500
If I can survive that, I can survive a glass of whiskey.

34:41.500 --> 34:43.500
Yeah.

35:12.500 --> 35:15.500
The Darkest Night.

35:39.500 --> 35:40.500
Sophie.

35:41.500 --> 35:42.500
You awake?

35:42.500 --> 35:43.500
Yes.

35:43.500 --> 35:45.500
Can you look at the map?

35:45.500 --> 35:46.500
Sorry?

35:46.500 --> 35:47.500
Sophie, wake up.

35:47.500 --> 35:48.500
We're nearly there.

35:48.500 --> 35:49.500
Oh, right.

35:49.500 --> 35:51.500
Can you look at the map, please?

35:51.500 --> 35:52.500
What map?

35:52.500 --> 35:58.500
Sophie, we've just passed a place called Mold, which means that we must be getting near to Plastag.

35:58.500 --> 35:59.500
Where?

35:59.500 --> 36:00.500
Plastag.

36:00.500 --> 36:01.500
The place where we're going to stay.

36:01.500 --> 36:02.500
We're nearly there.

36:02.500 --> 36:05.500
So, why do I have to look on the map?

36:05.500 --> 36:08.500
Because I wrote some instructions on it.

36:08.500 --> 36:09.500
Sophie, hurry up.

36:09.500 --> 36:10.500
We may miss the turning.

36:10.500 --> 36:11.500
Tom, don't be angry with me.

36:11.500 --> 36:13.500
Well, well, I need your help.

36:13.500 --> 36:16.500
I can't drive and look at the map at the same time.

36:16.500 --> 36:17.500
Okay.

36:17.500 --> 36:18.500
Okay.

36:18.500 --> 36:19.500
Let me...

36:19.500 --> 36:20.500
Tom, look out!

36:20.500 --> 36:21.500
What?

36:21.500 --> 36:22.500
What is this?

36:22.500 --> 36:23.500
The girl!

36:23.500 --> 36:24.500
You're going to hit that girl!

36:24.500 --> 36:25.500
What girl?

36:25.500 --> 36:26.500
The girl in the road!

36:26.500 --> 36:27.500
Look out!

36:27.500 --> 36:28.500
Sophie, take your hand off the wheel.

36:28.500 --> 36:29.500
Oh!

36:29.500 --> 36:30.500
No!

36:34.500 --> 36:37.500
What the hell was all that about?

36:37.500 --> 36:39.500
Are you okay?

36:39.500 --> 36:41.500
I think so.

36:41.500 --> 36:44.500
But what about the girl?

36:44.500 --> 36:45.500
Did you hit her?

36:45.500 --> 36:48.500
What on earth are you talking about?

36:48.500 --> 36:51.500
Look, Sophie, I've just crashed the car into...

36:51.500 --> 36:54.500
What the hell is this?

36:54.500 --> 36:57.500
We've crashed into a great big mound of earth.

36:57.500 --> 37:01.500
There was a girl crossing the road, didn't you see her?

37:01.500 --> 37:03.500
No, I didn't see anyone.

37:03.500 --> 37:05.500
And anyway, look at the car.

37:05.500 --> 37:07.500
Oh my God, if you hit her, she could be dead.

37:07.500 --> 37:09.500
I didn't hit anyone.

37:09.500 --> 37:11.500
There was no one on the road.

37:11.500 --> 37:13.500
What's the matter with you?

37:13.500 --> 37:14.500
Were you dreaming?

37:14.500 --> 37:15.500
No!

37:15.500 --> 37:17.500
I saw a girl.

37:17.500 --> 37:19.500
She stepped right in front of the car.

37:19.500 --> 37:21.500
And she looked straight at me.

37:21.500 --> 37:23.500
It was as if she wanted to kill herself.

37:23.500 --> 37:25.500
Well, she nearly killed us.

37:25.500 --> 37:28.500
Sophie, where are you going?

37:28.500 --> 37:30.500
I'm going to look for her!

37:31.500 --> 37:34.500
Oh, please, God, let her be OK.

37:34.500 --> 37:36.500
Can you see anything?

37:36.500 --> 37:38.500
No.

37:38.500 --> 37:40.500
Oh, there's no one here.

37:40.500 --> 37:42.500
I told you there wasn't anyone.

37:42.500 --> 37:45.500
Tom, I saw a girl.

37:45.500 --> 37:48.500
She stepped out into the road in front of the car.

37:48.500 --> 37:50.500
What did she look like?

37:50.500 --> 37:52.500
She was young.

37:52.500 --> 37:54.500
She looked about 14 and...

37:54.500 --> 37:56.500
And what?

37:56.500 --> 37:58.500
Well, she looked...

37:58.500 --> 38:01.500
I don't know. She looked old-fashioned.

38:01.500 --> 38:04.500
I've never seen anyone who looked like that.

38:04.500 --> 38:08.500
And she was carrying something, a kind of bag.

38:08.500 --> 38:10.500
They looked really old.

38:10.500 --> 38:13.500
Sophie, I don't think you actually saw anyone.

38:13.500 --> 38:16.500
I think you were still half asleep.

38:16.500 --> 38:17.500
Maybe.

38:17.500 --> 38:20.500
Anyway, we have to do something about the car.

38:25.500 --> 38:27.500
Let's see if I can start it.

38:29.500 --> 38:30.500
No.

38:30.500 --> 38:32.500
OK.

38:39.500 --> 38:42.500
Well, this car isn't going anywhere.

38:42.500 --> 38:44.500
What did we hit?

38:44.500 --> 38:47.500
Well, I thought it was just a moment of Earth.

38:50.500 --> 38:53.500
But it's really solid.

38:53.500 --> 38:57.500
It's some kind of round wall or something.

38:58.500 --> 38:59.500
Oh.

38:59.500 --> 39:01.500
What is it?

39:01.500 --> 39:03.500
I think it's a well.

39:03.500 --> 39:06.500
A well? What, like for water?

39:06.500 --> 39:07.500
Yes.

39:07.500 --> 39:10.500
Well, it used to be a well. It's...

39:10.500 --> 39:12.500
It's been filled in.

39:12.500 --> 39:14.500
Right.

39:14.500 --> 39:17.500
So, what are we going to do about the car?

39:17.500 --> 39:20.500
Oh, try to call someone.

39:20.500 --> 39:22.500
Oh.

39:22.500 --> 39:23.500
What?

39:23.500 --> 39:25.500
I can't get a signal.

39:25.500 --> 39:26.500
Can you?

39:26.500 --> 39:28.500
Wait a sec.

39:28.500 --> 39:30.500
No.

39:30.500 --> 39:32.500
I can't.

39:32.500 --> 39:34.500
Oh, not surprising, really.

39:34.500 --> 39:36.500
We're in the middle of nowhere.

39:36.500 --> 39:37.500
Oh.

39:37.500 --> 39:38.500
Look.

39:38.500 --> 39:39.500
What?

39:39.500 --> 39:40.500
The sign over there.

39:40.500 --> 39:41.500
Plus tag.

39:41.500 --> 39:42.500
Plus tag.

39:42.500 --> 39:43.500
Oh!

39:43.500 --> 39:45.500
The place where we're going to stay.

39:45.500 --> 39:46.500
Yes.

39:46.500 --> 39:47.500
Oh.

39:47.500 --> 39:49.500
It's two kilometers down that road.

39:49.500 --> 39:50.500
Two kilometers?

39:50.500 --> 39:51.500
Oh, no.

39:51.500 --> 39:52.500
It's not far.

39:52.500 --> 39:54.500
We can leave the luggage in the car.

39:54.500 --> 39:56.500
I'm not leaving anything in the car.

39:56.500 --> 39:58.500
It could get stolen.

39:58.500 --> 40:00.500
Sophie, what did you just say?

40:00.500 --> 40:02.500
We're in the middle of nowhere.

40:02.500 --> 40:04.500
No one is going to steal anything.

40:04.500 --> 40:07.500
I am not leaving anything in the car.

40:07.500 --> 40:10.500
Okay.

40:10.500 --> 40:13.500
Let's unpack and start walking.

40:20.500 --> 40:21.500
Grandma?

40:21.500 --> 40:23.500
What is it, Gwyn?

40:23.500 --> 40:26.500
There are two people walking down the path.

40:26.500 --> 40:27.500
Who are they?

40:27.500 --> 40:28.500
I don't know.

40:28.500 --> 40:30.500
They're not from around here.

40:30.500 --> 40:32.500
And they've got a lot of luggage.

40:32.500 --> 40:33.500
Really?

40:33.500 --> 40:35.500
Strange.

40:35.500 --> 40:39.500
I'm expecting some people from London, but they're coming by car.

40:39.500 --> 40:42.500
I wonder who these people are.

40:42.500 --> 40:43.500
Don't know.

40:43.500 --> 40:44.500
We'll go on.

40:44.500 --> 40:45.500
What?

40:45.500 --> 40:47.500
Go out and help them.

40:47.500 --> 40:49.500
Oh, okay.

40:50.500 --> 40:52.500
Nearly there.

40:52.500 --> 40:54.500
Oh, good.

40:54.500 --> 40:56.500
My feet are killing me.

40:56.500 --> 41:00.500
My arms are killing me from carrying all your luggage.

41:00.500 --> 41:03.500
I can't carry suitcases in these shoes.

41:03.500 --> 41:04.500
Right.

41:04.500 --> 41:05.500
Oh, look.

41:05.500 --> 41:06.500
Someone's coming.

41:06.500 --> 41:07.500
Hello?

41:07.500 --> 41:08.500
Hello?

41:08.500 --> 41:10.500
Have you come to stay at Plastag?

41:10.500 --> 41:11.500
Yes.

41:11.500 --> 41:12.500
Here.

41:12.500 --> 41:14.500
Let me give you a hand with your luggage.

41:14.500 --> 41:15.500
Thank you very much.

41:15.500 --> 41:17.500
Flippin' heck.

41:17.500 --> 41:18.500
This one's heavy.

41:18.500 --> 41:19.500
I know.

41:19.500 --> 41:22.500
I'll take this round the back of the house and up to your room.

41:22.500 --> 41:24.500
You win the bell and my grand will let you in.

41:24.500 --> 41:25.500
Okay.

41:25.500 --> 41:26.500
Thank you.

41:26.500 --> 41:28.500
Goodness.

41:28.500 --> 41:30.500
Look at this ancient bell.

41:30.500 --> 41:32.500
I wonder if it works.

41:32.500 --> 41:33.500
Yes.

41:33.500 --> 41:35.500
It does.

41:35.500 --> 41:36.500
Hello?

41:36.500 --> 41:37.500
Ah.

41:37.500 --> 41:45.500
You must be Mr. and Mrs. Parks.

41:45.500 --> 41:46.500
Is that right?

41:46.500 --> 41:47.500
Yes.

41:47.500 --> 41:52.500
Well, I'm Tom Parks and this is my partner, Sophie Richardson.

41:52.500 --> 41:53.500
Hello.

41:53.500 --> 41:55.500
Are you Mrs. Craven?

41:55.500 --> 41:57.500
Yes, that's right.

41:57.500 --> 41:59.500
Welcome to Plastag.

41:59.500 --> 42:03.500
Um, did you come by bus from mold?

42:03.500 --> 42:04.500
No.

42:04.500 --> 42:05.500
No.

42:05.500 --> 42:06.500
We came by car.

42:06.500 --> 42:07.500
Oh.

42:07.500 --> 42:08.500
So...

42:08.500 --> 42:10.500
We had an accident.

42:10.500 --> 42:14.500
I'm afraid I crashed into the old well at the corner of the main road.

42:14.500 --> 42:17.500
You crashed into the old well.

42:17.500 --> 42:20.500
How did you manage to do that?

42:20.500 --> 42:21.500
Well, I...

42:21.500 --> 42:23.500
It's a long story.

42:23.500 --> 42:26.500
Well, come inside.

42:26.500 --> 42:30.500
Right.

42:30.500 --> 42:32.500
This is your room.

42:32.500 --> 42:34.500
Oh, it's wonderful.

42:34.500 --> 42:35.500
Yes.

42:35.500 --> 42:36.500
It's brilliant.

42:36.500 --> 42:40.500
Mrs. Craven, is there a garage near here?

42:40.500 --> 42:43.500
Is there someone who can fix my car?

42:43.500 --> 42:45.500
I've already asked Green to call someone.

42:45.500 --> 42:46.500
Thank you.

42:46.500 --> 42:52.500
I hope you don't mind me asking, but how did the accident happen?

42:52.500 --> 42:54.500
Well, Sophie...

42:54.500 --> 42:58.500
I thought I saw someone step into the road, Mrs. Craven.

42:58.500 --> 43:00.500
I thought we were going to hit her.

43:00.500 --> 43:03.500
Someone stepped into the road.

43:03.500 --> 43:05.500
I think I was just dreaming.

43:05.500 --> 43:11.500
But you think you saw someone on the road at the junction with the road to this house?

43:11.500 --> 43:12.500
Yes.

43:13.500 --> 43:16.500
Can you describe the person that you saw?

43:16.500 --> 43:18.500
It was a girl.

43:18.500 --> 43:21.500
She was about 14.

43:21.500 --> 43:22.500
A girl?

43:22.500 --> 43:24.500
I see.

43:24.500 --> 43:28.500
Did you notice anything else about her?

43:28.500 --> 43:29.500
Yes.

43:29.500 --> 43:31.500
She was carrying an old bag.

43:31.500 --> 43:33.500
But I was half asleep.

43:33.500 --> 43:35.500
I think I was dreaming.

43:35.500 --> 43:36.500
Yes.

43:36.500 --> 43:39.500
Of course you were.

43:39.500 --> 43:41.500
Ah, here's Green.

43:50.500 --> 43:54.500
Gran, David Gower from the garage is here to look at the car.

43:54.500 --> 43:55.500
Great.

43:55.500 --> 43:58.500
Can you give us the keys and we'll go and see what we can do?

43:58.500 --> 44:01.500
Yes, of course. Here you are.

44:01.500 --> 44:03.500
Thanks.

44:04.500 --> 44:06.500
You know what? I'm hungry.

44:07.500 --> 44:10.500
Is there anywhere good to eat?

44:12.500 --> 44:16.500
Here it is. The Trevord Arts. Thank you.

44:16.500 --> 44:19.500
Good. I'm starving.

44:19.500 --> 44:21.500
Last three pounds.

44:21.500 --> 44:25.500
Here you are. Thank you. Enjoy your evening.

44:33.500 --> 44:34.500
It looks great.

44:34.500 --> 44:38.500
Yes, but what's the food like? Remember, we're in the middle of nowhere.

44:38.500 --> 44:40.500
Let's find out.

44:40.500 --> 44:41.500
Excuse me.

44:41.500 --> 44:42.500
Hello. Can I help you?

44:42.500 --> 44:43.500
Can we see a menu?

44:43.500 --> 44:45.500
It's on the wall.

44:45.500 --> 44:46.500
Sorry?

44:46.500 --> 44:51.500
We don't have a menu. The food we do is written on the wall. Over there.

44:51.500 --> 44:52.500
Oh, right.

44:52.500 --> 44:54.500
Do you want me to come back?

44:54.500 --> 44:56.500
No, I think we can order now.

44:56.500 --> 45:00.500
I think I'll have the steak pie, please.

45:00.500 --> 45:01.500
So...

45:05.500 --> 45:11.500
That was the most boring meal I've ever had in my life.

45:11.500 --> 45:12.500
Well...

45:12.500 --> 45:14.500
Have you finished?

45:14.500 --> 45:16.500
Yes, thank you. Was everything all right?

45:16.500 --> 45:17.500
Wonderful.

45:17.500 --> 45:18.500
Good.

45:18.500 --> 45:20.500
Can you tell me something?

45:20.500 --> 45:21.500
Yes.

45:21.500 --> 45:22.500
How old is this pub?

45:22.500 --> 45:24.500
Oh, it's very old.

45:24.500 --> 45:27.500
The original pub was built in 1500.

45:27.500 --> 45:28.500
1500?

45:28.500 --> 45:29.500
That's amazing.

45:29.500 --> 45:31.500
Well, that building.

45:31.500 --> 45:36.500
Burned down a long time ago, but this place is about 300 years old.

45:36.500 --> 45:39.500
And why is it called the Trevor Arms?

45:39.500 --> 45:43.500
Ah, well, it's named after the Trevor family.

45:43.500 --> 45:46.500
They used to be the landowners around here.

45:46.500 --> 45:50.500
They lived in a big house near here called Plasteg.

45:50.500 --> 45:52.500
Oh, we're staying there?

45:52.500 --> 45:53.500
Really?

45:53.500 --> 45:58.500
And is everything... is everything all right there?

45:58.500 --> 46:01.500
Yes, everything's fine. Why did you ask?

46:01.500 --> 46:04.500
Nothing. Excuse me.

46:04.500 --> 46:06.500
What was that about?

46:06.500 --> 46:08.500
What was what about?

46:08.500 --> 46:12.500
She seemed surprised that we were staying at Plasteg.

46:12.500 --> 46:15.500
Did she? She seemed quite okay to me.

46:15.500 --> 46:17.500
Anyway, shall we go?

46:17.500 --> 46:18.500
Okay.

46:18.500 --> 46:19.500
Oh, just...

46:19.500 --> 46:20.500
Tom?

46:20.500 --> 46:21.500
What?

46:21.500 --> 46:22.500
Look!

46:22.500 --> 46:23.500
What?

46:23.500 --> 46:24.500
At the window!

46:24.500 --> 46:25.500
What is it now?

46:25.500 --> 46:26.500
That girl again!

46:26.500 --> 46:29.500
Sophie, come back!

46:29.500 --> 46:31.500
What are you doing?

46:31.500 --> 46:33.500
I saw that girl again!

46:33.500 --> 46:34.500
Which girl?

46:34.500 --> 46:36.500
The girl we nearly ran down in the road.

46:36.500 --> 46:37.500
She was at the window!

46:37.500 --> 46:38.500
Where is she now?

46:38.500 --> 46:39.500
I don't know.

46:39.500 --> 46:40.500
She disappeared again.

46:40.500 --> 46:42.500
I think she's in the woods.

46:42.500 --> 46:44.500
Sophie, come back!

46:44.500 --> 46:46.500
I've got to find her!

46:46.500 --> 46:47.500
Stop!

46:47.500 --> 46:48.500
Sophie!

46:48.500 --> 46:51.500
I've got to find her!

46:51.500 --> 46:52.500
Stop!

46:52.500 --> 46:53.500
Sophie!

46:54.500 --> 46:55.500
Sophie!

47:01.500 --> 47:02.500
What the hell is going on?

47:02.500 --> 47:04.500
I don't know!

47:04.500 --> 47:05.500
Jesus!

47:05.500 --> 47:06.500
Tom!

47:06.500 --> 47:07.500
I'm scared!

47:07.500 --> 47:08.500
Me too!

47:08.500 --> 47:09.500
I...

47:09.500 --> 47:10.500
Tom!

47:10.500 --> 47:11.500
What?

47:11.500 --> 47:12.500
Look out!

47:12.500 --> 47:13.500
Oh God!

47:13.500 --> 47:15.500
Are you all right?

47:15.500 --> 47:16.500
No!

47:16.500 --> 47:17.500
Wait here!

47:17.500 --> 47:18.500
I'll get help!

47:18.500 --> 47:20.500
Go away!

47:20.500 --> 47:21.500
Who's there?

47:22.500 --> 47:24.500
Go away!

47:24.500 --> 47:25.500
Tom!

47:25.500 --> 47:26.500
It's the girl!

47:26.500 --> 47:27.500
Go away!

47:27.500 --> 47:30.500
I've never come near me again!

47:30.500 --> 47:34.500
If you do, something even worse will happen!

47:34.500 --> 47:37.500
Ahhh!

47:39.500 --> 47:40.500
Tom?

47:40.500 --> 47:42.500
Where am I?

47:42.500 --> 47:44.500
You're in hospital.

47:44.500 --> 47:45.500
In hospital?

47:45.500 --> 47:46.500
What?

47:46.500 --> 47:47.500
Oh!

47:47.500 --> 47:48.500
Don't try to move!

47:48.500 --> 47:50.500
What's the matter with me?

47:50.500 --> 47:54.500
You have a broken shoulder and a broken arm.

47:54.500 --> 47:56.500
You're lucky to be alive.

47:56.500 --> 47:58.500
What happened?

47:58.500 --> 48:00.500
A tree fell on you.

48:00.500 --> 48:02.500
Yeah.

48:02.500 --> 48:04.500
I remember now.

48:04.500 --> 48:07.500
Well, at least it wasn't that girl.

48:07.500 --> 48:09.500
It was that girl.

48:09.500 --> 48:11.500
I'm sure she was responsible.

48:11.500 --> 48:16.500
If you ever come near me again, something even worse will happen!

48:17.500 --> 48:22.500
When we were in the woods, she was there.

48:22.500 --> 48:26.500
When the tree fell on you, she was there.

48:26.500 --> 48:27.500
Sophie, listen.

48:27.500 --> 48:28.500
No, Tom.

48:28.500 --> 48:29.500
You listen to me.

48:29.500 --> 48:33.500
I am not the only one who has seen this girl.

48:33.500 --> 48:36.500
Everyone around here knows about her.

48:36.500 --> 48:40.500
That's why the waitress in the pub wanted to know if everything was all right.

48:40.500 --> 48:41.500
What waitress?

48:41.500 --> 48:45.500
And terrible things always happen when she appears.

48:45.500 --> 48:47.500
How do you know all this?

48:47.500 --> 48:49.500
Mrs. Craven told me.

48:49.500 --> 48:51.500
She's here.

48:51.500 --> 48:54.500
And she wants to tell us the whole story.

48:54.500 --> 48:55.500
Uh-huh.

48:55.500 --> 48:57.500
Are you ready for this?

48:57.500 --> 48:59.500
I guess so.

48:59.500 --> 49:01.500
I'll go and get her.

49:08.500 --> 49:10.500
Hello, Mrs. Craven.

49:10.500 --> 49:11.500
Mr. Parks.

49:11.500 --> 49:13.500
I'm so sorry.

49:13.500 --> 49:15.500
Don't be silly, Mrs. Craven.

49:15.500 --> 49:17.500
This isn't your fault.

49:17.500 --> 49:19.500
Well, maybe it is.

49:19.500 --> 49:20.500
Why?

49:20.500 --> 49:22.500
What do you mean?

49:22.500 --> 49:25.500
I should have warned you about the girl.

49:25.500 --> 49:28.500
Mrs. Craven, tell Tom what you told me.

49:28.500 --> 49:36.500
The girl that Sophie saw is someone who lived in my house five hundred years ago.

49:37.500 --> 49:44.500
The house was built by a man called Sir John Trevo, sometime around fifteen hundred.

49:44.500 --> 49:50.500
When he died, his brother Edward became the owner of the house.

49:50.500 --> 49:56.500
Ashes to ashes, dust to dust.

49:56.500 --> 50:00.500
We commend our dear brother to be heard.

50:01.500 --> 50:08.500
My Lord Trevo, allow me to express my deepest sympathy.

50:08.500 --> 50:10.500
Thank you, Squirt Rwellin.

50:10.500 --> 50:16.500
My Lord, is it true that you and your family will now live at Plasté?

50:16.500 --> 50:18.500
Correct, Squirt Rwellin.

50:18.500 --> 50:22.500
And in a few weeks' time, when we have finished mourning my dear brother John,

50:22.500 --> 50:27.500
we will have a feast and invite people from all over the county.

50:27.500 --> 50:33.500
And is it also true that your daughter Dorothy is already sixteen?

50:33.500 --> 50:40.500
She is indeed, in fact, she will be seventeen in just a few months, I see.

50:40.500 --> 50:45.500
Did you know that my son Alan finds her most desirable?

50:45.500 --> 50:48.500
I knew of this, Lwellin.

50:48.500 --> 50:56.500
It occurred to me that we may use the occasion of the feast to announce the betrudal of my son and your daughter.

50:57.500 --> 50:59.500
This was my idea, too.

50:59.500 --> 51:00.500
Dorothy?

51:00.500 --> 51:02.500
Yes, Father.

51:02.500 --> 51:05.500
I'm going to make an announcement to the servants.

51:05.500 --> 51:08.500
I would like you to be there when I do it.

51:08.500 --> 51:09.500
Yes, Father.

51:17.500 --> 51:19.500
Good morning, everyone.

51:19.500 --> 51:24.500
I, Edward Trevoire, am now a master of Plasté.

51:24.500 --> 51:30.500
And I want you to know that life in the great house will continue as before.

51:30.500 --> 51:34.500
Everyone will continue to do the work they are doing now.

51:34.500 --> 51:35.500
Oh, God bless you, sir.

51:35.500 --> 51:36.500
Oh, thank you.

51:36.500 --> 51:37.500
Thank you.

51:37.500 --> 51:38.500
Thank you.

51:38.500 --> 51:39.500
Thank you.

51:39.500 --> 51:44.500
For now, the house is in mourning for my dear brother.

51:44.500 --> 51:49.500
Very soon, we will have a great feast of celebration.

51:49.500 --> 51:57.500
And the cause of celebration will be the announcement of the marriage of my daughter Dorothy to Alan Lwellin.

52:05.500 --> 52:08.500
Young Miss Dorothy is to marry Alan Lwellin.

52:08.500 --> 52:10.500
I cannot believe it.

52:10.500 --> 52:13.500
Alan Lwellin, such a horrible man.

52:14.500 --> 52:16.500
And did you see the young girl's face?

52:16.500 --> 52:19.500
She didn't look very happy about the idea.

52:19.500 --> 52:20.500
You're right.

52:20.500 --> 52:22.500
She looked shocked.

52:29.500 --> 52:35.500
So, Dorothy, you are to be married in June on the occasion of your 17th birthday.

52:35.500 --> 52:39.500
Father, this is not what I expected.

52:39.500 --> 52:41.500
Not what you expected.

52:41.500 --> 52:42.500
What do you mean?

52:42.500 --> 52:45.500
I feel I am not ready for marriage.

52:45.500 --> 52:47.500
Not ready.

52:47.500 --> 52:50.500
Dorothy, you're nearly 17.

52:50.500 --> 52:52.500
Nearly half way through your life.

52:52.500 --> 52:54.500
Of course you are ready.

53:00.500 --> 53:04.500
Well, Miss Dorothy, you are to be married.

53:04.500 --> 53:05.500
Annie, listen.

53:05.500 --> 53:06.500
Yes, Miss.

53:06.500 --> 53:08.500
You are the only person I can trust.

53:08.500 --> 53:10.500
Yes, Miss.

53:10.500 --> 53:13.500
You know that I do not love Alan Lwellin.

53:13.500 --> 53:15.500
Oh, Miss Dorothy.

53:15.500 --> 53:18.500
I am in love with Yvonne Turner.

53:18.500 --> 53:20.500
Yvonne Turner?

53:20.500 --> 53:24.500
But Yvonne Turner is just a farm hand.

53:24.500 --> 53:26.500
